<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 2 日星期三 05:04:33 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Meta Platforms Begins Blocking News for Canadian Users]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这些变化是为了响应旨在为国内媒体获得赔偿的立法<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101891"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827696?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大议会已通过立法，强制数字平台对媒体机构的链接进行补偿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ralph Lauer/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101891"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 6:24（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>渥太华——经过数月的警告， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>周二表示，它已开始阻止加拿大 Facebook 和 Instagram 用户访问新闻链接，这加大了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-passes-law-forcing-facebook-google-to-pay-media-for-links-f3e13300?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数字公司</a>是否应该为新闻媒体提供资金的摊牌风险。</p><p> Meta 发言人安迪·斯通 (Andy Stone) 在<a href="https://twitter.com/andymstone/status/1686415795184717825?s=46&amp;t=eebdHRjEkuwPcPHUk0BFTA" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">X（该平台以前称为 Twitter）的官方账户</a>上表示：“变化将在几周内推出。” “正如我们一直说的，法律是建立在一个根本上有缺陷的前提之上的。遗憾的是，我们合理遵守的唯一方法是停止在加拿大提供新闻。”</p><p> Meta 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a><span class="company-name-type">旗下的</span>谷歌对加拿大议会 6 月通过的立法采取了强硬立场，该立法迫使数字平台向媒体机构提供链接补偿。互联网法律专家和前科技行业高管表示，这一立场反映了公司对传染效应的担忧——每个司法管辖区都会试图模仿加拿大的做法，让硅谷公司帮助资助新闻采访。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827935?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meta Platforms 表示，加拿大立法的前提存在根本性缺陷。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jeff Chiu/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国参议院司法委员会已经批准了<a href="https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/press/releases/senate-judiciary-committee-advances-bipartisan-bill-to-preserve-strong-independent-journalism-and-news-organizations" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">拟议的立法</a>，其范围与加拿大批准的立法相似， <a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=202320240AB886" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">加利福尼亚州的州立法者</a>正在讨论一项要求科技行业向州媒体组织付费的法案。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-zealand-plans-to-make-facebook-google-pay-for-news-11670225540?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新西兰去年提出了一项提案</a>，说服数字平台与当地新闻媒体达成自愿协议，南非和巴西正在考虑监管。</p><p>谷歌表示，当当局开始执行该立法时，它将删除<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-to-block-canada-news-links-from-search-function-in-response-to-law-9fb56046?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">针对加拿大用户的搜索功能的加拿大新闻文章的链接</a>，预计将在今年年底法规最终确定时实施。加拿大官员表示，他们相信自己能够解决谷歌的担忧。谷歌发言人周二表示，其计划仍然有效。</p><p> Meta 对加拿大链接的决定类似于 2021 年 2 月因内容付费纠纷而屏蔽澳大利亚 Facebook 平台新闻的举措。几天后，Meta 在获得澳大利亚政府的让步后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-says-agreement-reached-with-australian-government-to-restore-news-11614055767?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消了禁令</a>。 Meta 的举动引起了美国、欧洲和英国的批评</p><p>加拿大没有妥协的迹象。梅塔在一份声明中表示：“我们一直保持透明，并向加拿大政府明确表示，该立法歪曲了新闻媒体在选择使用我们平台时所获得的价值。” “这项立法是基于错误的前提，即 Meta 从我们平台上共享的新闻内容中获得不公平的利益，而事实恰恰相反。”</p><p>渥太华大学专门研究互联网法的教授迈克尔·盖斯特表示，他预计 Meta 不会改变主意。他说：“全世界都在关注，鉴于其他国家可能会出台法律来解决对媒体的支持问题，Meta 敏锐地意识到，改变其在加拿大的立场就等于邀请其他国家出台类似的立法。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>贾斯汀·特鲁多总理</p>将与 Meta 和 Google 的战斗比作第二次世界大战。 “他们决定攻击加拿大，这是一个错误的选择，”他在七月告诉记者。 “加拿大人不会被美国亿万富翁欺负”<p></p><p>上周作为内阁改革的一部分被任命为加拿大遗产部长的帕斯卡尔·圣翁格 (Pascale St-Onge) 周二表示，Meta 的决定是不负责任的，因为截至目前，该公司不承担任何法律义务，因为法规尚未起草。</p><p> St-Onge 表示：“Facebook 不仅试图向加拿大传达信息，还向新西兰、英国和美国等其他国家传达信息。” “如果政府不能支持加拿大人对抗科技巨头，谁会呢？”</p><p> Meta 最近已经不再关注新闻，而是将重点放在向 Facebook 和 Instagram 用户展示由人工智能驱动的系统向他们推荐的内容上。该公司特别重视Reels，这是该公司与TikTok竞争的短视频内容。</p><p>继 7 月份推出 Meta 的微博线程服务之后，</p> Instagram 负责人 Adam Mosseri 在一篇帖子中表示，该公司<a href="https://www.threads.net/@mosseri/post/CuZ3LjhNl0m" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">不会在新应用上做任何</a>鼓励政治和新闻的事情。<p></p><p>加拿大法律要求数字平台与新闻出版商就其内容达成商业协议，新闻出版商包括印刷媒体、在线媒体和广播媒体。目标是为媒体机构提供财务生命线，以抵消迁移到数字领域的广告收入损失。如果谈判失败，立法要求双方进行具有约束力的仲裁，以确定适当的赔偿。</p><p> Meta 和谷歌都认为，该法律将对网页的免费链接定价，这违反了版权法，并颠覆了开放互联网的概念，即用户可以不受限制地搜索和连接到材料。加拿大官员表示，最终法规将包括限制数字公司向新闻媒体支付的费用。</p><p>新闻出版商游说团体加拿大新闻媒体总裁兼首席执行官保罗·迪根 (Paul Deegan) 表示，“梅塔单方面与加拿大‘解除友好关系’的行为是过分的。”他补充说，“建议 Meta 参与其中，以确保法规对所有人来说都是公平、平衡和可预测的。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——旧金山的萨尔瓦多·罗德里格斯 (Salvador Rodriguez) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给保罗·维埃拉 (Paul Vieira)： <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 22:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母 C1A</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Countries Raid Each Others’ Health Systems in Global Battle for Nurses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>医疗人员短缺导致全球范围内猖獗的偷猎行为，激怒了较贫穷的国家<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826463/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。华尔街日报的布莱恩·<span>凯西 华尔街日报的布莱恩·凯西</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stuart-condie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯图尔特·康迪</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 4:34（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>全球医疗保健工作者短缺正在引发一场激烈的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-pay-for-covid-19-nurses-leads-to-shortages-at-some-hospitals-11630253483?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球人才争夺战</a>，富裕国家纷纷从其他国家的医疗系统中寻找工作人员来照顾老龄化人口。</p><p>这项竞赛帮助美国和澳大利亚等国家替换了一些在Covid-19大流行最严重期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-surge-leaves-doctors-nurses-reeling-from-burnout-11611612044?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞职的</a>护士。但这也让发展中国家和英国等一些富裕国家的医院处境更糟，因为它们的员工流向了工资更高的国家。</p><p>澳大利亚一直是最激进的偷猎者之一，提供特别奖金和快速签证。去年冬天，澳大利亚在不列颠群岛进行了一场广告活动，广告中的工人身后的窗户洒满了阳光。此次活动恰逢英国护士因工资、长时间工作和其他问题而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-nurses-stage-biggest-ever-strike-as-health-system-strains-11671121289?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">举行罢工</a>。</p><p> “你可以在清晨冲浪，周末去飞蝇钓鱼，参加摄影课程，写小说，或者在农贸市场出售蜜饯，”行业杂志《英国医学杂志》上的一则急救药物广告说道。登记员的工作。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>投放这则广告的澳大利亚塔斯马尼亚州卫生部门表示，与其他地方当局一样，该部门正在向包括英国在内的许多国家寻找海外工人。</p><p>这场战斗是今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">全球移民潮复苏</a>的一部分，这场移民潮正在重塑世界经济。自疫情最严重时期以来，随着边境重新开放，各国一直欢迎特定行业的外国工人，以解决劳动力短缺问题，帮助将移民人数推至创纪录水平。</p><p>津巴布韦圭鲁省医院的护士道格拉斯·奇科布武(Douglas Chikobvu)表示，近年来，他看到外科病房的大约十几名护士搬到国外工作。</p><p>津巴布韦专业护士联盟秘书长 Chikobvu 表示，在一些医院，一名护士有时在轮班期间要照顾 25 或 30 名患者，而不是更合理的 10 名患者。医生被迫取消手术因为他们没有足够的员工。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826697?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">护士道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 表示，护士们已经离开津巴布韦到国外工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826789?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月，护士们在津巴布韦一家医院外示威，要求提高工资。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：aaron ufumeli/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>津巴布韦副总统康斯坦丁诺·奇文加</p>身兼卫生部长的他四月份威胁说，他的国家将通过一项新法律，将积极招募津巴布韦医护人员定为犯罪行为。<p></p><p>英国政府今年公布的数据显示，截至 3 月 31 日的 12 个月内，仅英国就向津巴布韦国民发放了 17,421 份医疗和护理人员签证，几乎是前 12 个月的六倍。</p><p>奇温加在四月份的一次关于人口贩运的活动上发表讲话时，将招募发展中国家医务人员称为“反人类罪”。</p><p>他说：“如果人们因为没有护士和医生而死在医院，而且有人如此不负责任地不培训自己的国民，而是希望贫穷国家为他们提供培训，那么这就是一种必须严肃对待的犯罪行为。”</p><p>世界卫生组织今年 3 月公布了 55 个国家（其中 37 个在非洲）面临最紧迫的卫生劳动力挑战的名单。这些国家平均每 10,000 人只有 15 名卫生工作者，而高收入国家每 10,000 人有 148 名卫生工作者。</p><p>世界卫生组织已要求其成员国在未首先签署双边协议以支持招募国家的情况下，不要积极从这 55 个国家招募医生和护士。此类支持可能包括资助新员工的培训或计划让卫生工作者在几年后返回原籍国。</p><p>对于富裕国家来说，吸引国外医务人员很有吸引力，因为培训护士和医生可能需要数年时间。 《健康事务》杂志的一项研究显示，2020 年至 2021 年间， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurse-shortage-hospitals-hiring-gig-economy-dc94bdb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国失去了超过 10 万名护士</a>，这是有记录以来的最大降幅。</p><p>自疫情最严重以来，医院一直在努力重建正常的人员配备水平和士气。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurses-flock-back-to-hospitals-after-leaving-in-the-pandemic-4f94b591?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">此后，工资和工作条件的改善吸引了一些工人回来</a>，但短缺仍然存在。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826724?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 前往津巴布韦圭鲁省医院工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826698?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 在家里挂着制服，他说，在津巴布韦的一些医院，一名护士一个班次就可以照顾 25 到 30 名患者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据澳大利亚统计局的最新数据，在澳大利亚，从 2020 年初到 2022 年 8 月，广告中的卫生专业人员职位空缺数量增加了一倍多，并在 9 个月后仍接近历史峰值。</p><p>根据澳大利亚内政部的数据，截至 2023 年 3 月的 9 个月内，该国向医护人员发放了 4,950 份签证。官员们表示，这个数字比一年前增加了 48%，但该国仍然面临护士短缺的问题。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/RHC" class="">Ramsay Health Care</a>在澳大利亚和其他 10 个国家拥有 500 多家医院和诊所<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司最近表示，技术工人的缺乏继续限制了其治疗患者的能力。据称，该公司正在海外寻找员工。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生正在英国北部工作，一家招聘机构找到她，询问她是否有兴趣搬到澳大利亚。 11 月移居澳大利亚后，她现在在凯恩斯工作，凯恩斯是澳大利亚北部的一个城市，被称为通往大堡礁的门户。</p><p>康说，她现在的年收入比在英国高出约 56,000 美元，部分原因是州政府为改善大城市以外的职位而提供补贴。她每天的通勤方式是沿着海滨骑自行车。</p><p>一月份从爱尔兰搬到澳大利亚的放射科医生丽贝卡·戴利 (Rebekah Daly) 表示，由于与新冠病毒相关的旅行限制已经取消，她在家乡的同事中近四分之一已经辞职去海外旅行或工作，这增加了这些人的工作量被留下来。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="909" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826464?width=1260&amp;height=909" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">自行车是 Hardeep Kang 博士在澳大利亚日常通勤的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的布莱恩·卡西</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="905" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826737?width=1260&amp;height=905" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">她说她现在在澳大利亚的年收入比在英国多约 56,000 美元</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的布莱恩·卡西</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>英国为医疗保健工作者推出了新签证，其规定比其他技术工人的繁琐规定要少。根据政府数据，截至 3 月 31 日的 12 个月内，该国向医疗和护理人员发放了 101,570 份签证，几乎是去年的三倍，其中大多数新员工来自印度、尼日利亚和津巴布韦。</p><p>世界卫生组织名单公布后，英国政府表示，卫生和社会保健组织不会积极从该机构标记的国家招募人员，但没有什么可以阻止这些国家的卫生工作者申请空缺职位。</p><p>爱尔兰在大流行之前严重依赖海外卫生工作者，去年放宽了对已在该国的非欧洲医生的就业限制，作为留住他们的努力的一部分。</p><p>据世界卫生组织称，近年来已有 70 多个国家出台了法律，以方便从国外聘用卫生工作者。德国等其他富裕国家已将招募医护人员作为高层访问加纳、巴西和阿尔巴尼亚等国的一部分。</p><p>在美国， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/green-card-backlog-fuels-shortage-of-nurses-at-hospitals-nursing-homes-4f0b0e44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">从国外招募护士实际上已经停止</a>，因为医疗机构用来雇用护士的绿卡类型已经被超额认购，以至于国务院停止处理申请。截至 9 月份的过去两个财年，包括注册护士和职业护士在内的海外医疗工作者的签证筛查请求均增长了 40% 以上。</p><p>总部位于纽约的 Adex Medical Staffing 招聘总监贾斯汀·莱博维茨 (Justin Leibowitz) 表示，积压意味着今年夏天招聘的护士可能需要长达四年的时间才能在美国开始工作，这使美国的人力资源公司和医疗保健雇主在全球范围内处于不利地位。</p><p> Adex 预先投入资金帮助国际护士满足在美国工作的要求，但直到护士开始工作后，该公司才能收回这笔资金。他表示，这些延误要求该公司需要等待更长的时间才能获得投资回报。国际护士也可能会重新考虑他们的选择。</p><p>莱博维茨表示，随着联邦财政年度的开始，绿卡积压情况可能会有所缓解，这可能会改善招聘前景。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>全球医疗资源短缺问题该如何解决？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>一些发展中国家正在采取措施，加大卫生工作者移民的难度。</p><p>长期以来，许多医护人员都流失到美国，菲律宾在疫情期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-heightens-global-struggle-for-migrant-nurses-11588161393?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">实施了临时禁令，禁止更多医护人员离开</a>。它继续限制可以在海外工作的人数，尽管这样做会剥夺该国急需的汇款收入。</p><p>尼日利亚立法者正在考虑一项法案，要求医生在家工作至少五年才能获准移民。</p><p>负责监督人员配置的津巴布韦卫生服务委员会表示，该国需要 81,517 名医护人员才能满足人口需求，但截至去年 9 月，该国仅有 74,298 名医护人员。</p><p>津巴布韦圭鲁省医院的护士 Chikobvu 表示，他和同事在专门的 WhatsApp 群组中分享美国和英国等国家的招聘广告。</p><p>尽管看到了他的国家医疗人才流失的影响，奇科布武目前正在美国申请护理工作，并反对限制富裕国家从贫穷国家雇用护士。</p><p>他说，他的月收入约为 425 美元，不足以支付家人的食品和医疗费用，也不足以支付四个孩子的学费。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826712?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">道格拉斯·奇科布武 (Douglas Chikobvu) 和他的女儿在津巴布韦。某护士工会秘书长称，目前正在美国申请护士工作</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> ——梅兰妮·埃文斯对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Stuart Condie <a href="mailto:stuart.condie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（stuart.condie@wsj.com）</a>和 Gabriele Steinhauser（ <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gabriele.steinhauser@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 20:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429<author><![CDATA[Stuart CondieGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>拉姆齐医疗保健</category><category>澳大利亚RHC</category><category>澳大利亚：RHC</category><category>道格拉斯·奇科布武</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tensions Between Russian, Western Allies Grow Over Niger Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>西非国家选边站，欧洲国家从尼日尔撤离公民<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827574?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，法国国民聚集在一起等待从尼日尔空运。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/noemie-bisserbe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Noemie Bisserbe</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoit Faucon</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gabriele Steinhauser</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日下午 2:48（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔上周发生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-general-declares-himself-leader-as-russian-mercenary-hails-coup-d47efa68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">政变，引发莫斯科在该</a>地区的盟友与与美国和其他西方大国合作更密切的国家之间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的紧张对峙，</a>随后欧洲各国政府于周二开始从尼日尔撤离本国公民。</p><p>由尼日尔前殖民国家法国领导的撤离行动表明，欧洲各国政府预计其公民在该国面临更高的风险，这对于美国打击萨赫勒地区伊斯兰武装分子的努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">至关重要</a>。萨赫勒地区是撒哈拉以南的半干旱地带。 。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>西方官员担心，上周拘留尼日尔当选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆的军政府可能会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-need-of-allies-putin-courts-african-leaders-in-st-petersburg-b6596a7b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯发展更密切的关系</a>，特别是如果法国和美国削减对军政府的军事援助。周日，数千名支持政变的抗议者向法国驻首都尼亚美大使馆投掷石块，其中一些人挥舞着俄罗斯国旗和标语牌，要求法国退出尼日尔。</p><p> “鉴于尼亚美的局势、前天针对我国大使馆发生的暴力事件以及领空的关闭，导致我们的同胞无法通过自己的方式离开该国，法国正在准备撤离其国民，希望离开该国的欧洲国民，”法国外交部周二表示。 “疏散行动将于今天开始，”它补充道。</p><p>意大利外交部长安东尼奥·塔亚尼(Antonio Tajani)在社交媒体平台X（前身为Twitter）上表示，意大利政府将派遣一架航班飞往尼亚美，帮助意大利国民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffrance-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>白宫国家安全委员会发言人约翰·柯比表示，目前没有从尼日尔撤离美国公民的计划。</p><p>柯比说：“我们确实是每小时都在关注这一情况，如果我们必须做出调整，我们就会做出调整——只是我们现在不在那儿。”</p><p>近年来，美国政府斥资约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，并在该国驻扎了约 1,100 名士兵和无人机。</p><p>这场由尼日尔强大的总统卫队领导的政变暴露了西非邻国之间的深刻分歧，其中几个邻国的民选政府在最近几周也被军队推翻。</p><p>西非国家经济共同体（以非洲最大经济体尼日利亚为主导，与尼日尔接壤 1,000 英里的边界）的领导人都大力支持巴祖姆。该组织被称为西非经济共同体，对尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">实施严厉的金融和贸易制裁</a>，并表示，如果军政府未能在本周末之前恢复巴祖姆的权力，他们将考虑进行军事干预。</p><p>这一威胁促使马里和布基纳法索（尼日尔的两个邻国在政变后与莫斯科结盟）的军事领导人发出警告，称他们将帮助保卫尼日尔军政府免受西非经共体的干预。</p><p>美国苏丹问题特使前幕僚长卡梅伦·哈德森表示，双方可能都在虚张声势地谈论军事对抗，双方都对更广泛的地区冲突不感兴趣。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827265?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">抗议者举着从法国驻尼亚美大使馆拿走的标语。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>哈德森说，马里和布基纳法索已经在本国边境与圣战武装分子作战，而国内也反对对尼日利亚军队进行武装干预，而尼日利亚军队必须领导这样的任务。他说，尽管如此，马里和布基纳法索的警告“提高了西非经共体干预的风险和成本”，并凸显了莫斯科对该地区的控制。</p><p>法国外交部长</p>凯瑟琳·科隆纳周一否认了尼日尔军政府关于巴黎将参与军事干预的说法。 “法国唯一的优先事项是其国民的安全，”她在晚间电视采访中说。<p></p><p>科隆纳指责军政府和俄罗斯对法国大使馆的袭击负责。</p><p> “我们（周日）看到的是一场有组织的、非自发的、暴力的、极其危险的抗议活动，其中有燃烧瓶、俄罗斯国旗、反法口号，都是从我们在其他地方看到的复制粘贴的，”她说。 “所以所有常见的俄罗斯-非洲风格的不稳定因素都是如此。”</p><p>外交部官员表示，约有 1,200 名法国公民居住在尼日尔，尽管其中许多人目前正在国外度假。法国国防部表示，这一数字不包括驻扎在尼日尔并将留在那里的约 1,500 名法国士兵。</p><p>法国外交部官员表示，他们正在与美国就可能撤离美国公民的事宜进行联系。</p><p> 2013年，在社会党总统弗朗索瓦·奥朗德的领导下，法国向萨赫勒地区部署了军队，帮助打击伊斯兰国和与基地组织有联系的武装分子。在马里和布基纳法索发生政变后，它被迫缩减在尼日尔的存在，并将精力集中在巴祖姆的盟友尼日尔。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Michael M. Phillips 和 Gordon Lubold 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Noemie Bisserbe ( <a href="mailto:noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com</a> )、Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Gabriele Steinhauser ( <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 18:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af<author><![CDATA[Noemie BisserbeBenoit FauconGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Replaces Missile Commander Days After Removing Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>分析人士称，罢免高级军事领导人旨在增强对习近平的忠诚度<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827252?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国领导人习近平晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：李刚/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alastair-gale" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿拉斯泰尔·盖尔 (Alastair Gale)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄春汉 (Chun Han Wong)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 9:53（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国罢黜了导弹部队司令，分析人士称此举是为了确保军队对领导人习近平的忠诚，这支军队控制着针对美国的核弹头导弹，并将在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-china-ukraine-russia-hong-kong-military-war-517b87d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">任何夺取美国领土的企图</a>中发挥关键作用。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-china-ukraine-russia-hong-kong-military-war-517b87d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">台湾</a>通过武力。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军老兵李玉超的免职，标志着他在重要军事岗位上异常短暂的任期的突然结束，而几天前<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，中国又做出了一项神秘的决定，更换了外交部长</a>。</p><p>去年1月被任命为司令员的李已经好几个月没有在公开场合露面了。周二，中国庆祝中国人民解放军成立 96 周年，前一天举行的仪式上确认了他的下台。</p><p>在周二的周年纪念评论中，官方报纸《解放军报》敦促全体军人维护习近平作为共产党领导“核心”的地位，并坚持不懈地在军队内部执行纪律和反腐败工作。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。中国领导人习近平七个月前亲自挑选了秦国。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>据官方消息，在一天前的仪式上，习近平正式晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔，并向他们授予新军衔徽章。新华社．王和徐分别拥有海军和空军背景，他们的任命背离了中国战略导弹部队由具有该军种经验的军官指挥的长期做法。</p><p>麻省理工学院教授泰勒·弗拉维尔（Taylor Fravel）撰写了大量有关中国军队的文章，他表示，任命火箭军以外官员的决定表明，李所发现的问题非常严重，也反映了这支部队的重要性。在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国关系恶化的</a>情况下经历了显着扩张。</p><p>在中国对军队实行苏联式政治控制的情况下，解放军维持着双重领导体制，军事单位通常由两名同等级别的军官领导：一名指挥官，对作战决策拥有正式权力；以及执行党的指示的政委。</p><p>新华社的报道没有提及自 2020 年 7 月起担任这一职务的前任司令员李彦宏或政委。中国国防部没有立即回应有关李彦宏接任火箭军司令员的询问。</p><p>李克强离职几天前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国突然解除了</a>外交部长秦刚的职务，而就在秦刚上任几个月后，这是北京方面在没有任何解释的情况下做出的又一改变。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827253?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国最近解除了秦刚的外交部长职务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Thomas Trutschel/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>秦解职后不久，“对负责监督中国核武器计划的习近平心腹的前火箭军司令员李玉超的清洗，标志着中国多年来最深刻的领导层改组之一，”克雷格·辛格尔顿说。</p>保卫民主基金会的高级研究员，该基金会是一家总部位于华盛顿的保守派智囊团。<p></p><p>习近平于 2012 年底掌权后，在中国军队中开展了大范围的反腐败打击行动，清洗了多名高级指挥员，其中包括 2019 年被判处无期徒刑<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-chinese-military-chief-sentenced-to-life-in-prison-for-corruption-11550666372" target="_blank" class="icon none">的前联合参谋长房峰辉。</a>尽管近年来披露针对高级军官的调查的情况有所减少，但称这些清洗对于习近平将解放军打造成一支现代化战斗力量的努力至关重要。</p><p>辛格尔顿表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-wagner-revolt-questions-of-blame-in-vladimir-putins-inner-circle-64c541ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，俄罗斯最近发生的短暂武装起义</a>可能提醒人们需要严格控制军队。</p><p> “瓦格纳叛乱的失败几乎肯定强化了习近平对意识形态控制的执着，甚至不惜牺牲经济增长和中国正在进行的军事现代化，”他说。</p><p>解放军火箭军控制着中国的常规和核陆基导弹计划，包括能够到达美国本土的核弹头洲际弹道导弹。五角大楼在去年的一份报告中表示，北京近年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-is-accelerating-its-nuclear-buildup-over-rising-fears-of-u-s-conflict-11649509201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了核武器的发展</a>，预计到 2035 年，拥有的核弹头将从目前的约 400 枚增至约 1,500 枚。</p><p>美国战略司令部司令在今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-has-more-icbm-launchers-than-u-s-american-military-reports-11675779463" target="_blank" class="icon none">给国会的一封信中写道</a>，中国在西部沙漠地区建造了巨大的洲际弹道导弹发射井，目前拥有的导弹发射装置比美国还多。</p><p>尽管习近平领导了中国军队总体规模的缩减，但解放军火箭军近年来有所壮大，这反映出其对北京利用远程核弹头弹道导弹威慑美国和发展常规导弹的战略的重要性用于任何地区冲突的武库。</p><p>根据<a href="https://nonproliferation.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/web_peoples_liberation_army_rocket_force_order_of_battle_07102023.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近的一项研究</a>，过去十年，中国的战斗导弹旅数量增加了一倍。</p><p>解放军火箭军拥有数百枚弹道导弹，可用于瞄准台湾，企图强行控制该岛或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-missile-threat-drives-new-u-s-approach-in-asia-95fc9a7b" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁美国在日本和关岛的主要军事基地</a>。中国还部署了高超音速导弹，美国一直在努力开发这种导弹，而且导弹防御系统更难摧毁这种导弹。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军正在增强可信可靠的核威慑和反击能力，加强中远程精确打击力量，增强战略制衡能力，建设强大的现代化火箭军。 2019年最新的国防白皮书。</p><p>新的领导层任命标志着从军队其他部门引进指挥官的罕见决定。王新任火箭军司令员，曾任中国人民解放军海军副司令员。新任火箭军政委徐是一名空军军官，最近担任解放军南部战区副政委，该司令部负责南海地区，而南海是中美<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-jet-fighters-step-up-pressure-on-u-s-aircraft-over-south-china-sea-c2d1ac88" target="_blank" class="icon none">军事冲突频繁的</a>地区。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827254?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北京阅兵式上展示的弹道导弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mark Schiefelbein/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>关于李克强的副手刘广斌的命运也引发了猜测，他也已经几个月没有在公开场合露面了。官方媒体没有提及刘的地位，也没有提及任何替代者。</p><p>新的任命还意味着，火箭军现在有一位政治委员，其党龄高于指挥官，这是相当不寻常的。即将离任的司令员李和前政委徐忠波都是党的精英中央委员会的正式成员。</p><p>新任司令员王既不是中央委员，也不是无投票权的候补中央委员。新政委徐锡生是10月加入中央委员会的205名正式委员之一。</p><p>即使按照中国军方不透明的标准，与火箭军相关的细节也常常被严格隐瞒。</p><p>周一升职几天前，中国一家知名新闻媒体《澎湃新闻》援引已故军官的亲友的话称，一名前火箭军副司令于7月初去世，享年66岁。这份报告后来消失了。该报没有回应置评请求。</p><p>写信给 Alastair Gale <a href="mailto:alastair.gale@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（alastair.gale@wsj.com）</a>和 Chun Han Wong（ <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 13:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b<author><![CDATA[Alastair GaleChun Han Wong]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing Area Hit by Deadliest Flooding in a Decade]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>台风“多克苏里”横扫中国东部地区 至少20人死亡19人失踪<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=25BC57F5-3EBC-423B-9947-C966AF672A13&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbeijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">强台风给中国北方地区带来暴雨和严重洪涝灾害，造成北京及周边地区至少20人死亡。据中国官方媒体报道，数千人被迫逃离家园。照片：路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-liang" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷切尔·梁</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-strumpf" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·斯特朗普夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>据官方媒体报道，台风“多克苏里”带来的暴雨造成洪水连续第四天，北京及周边地区至少有 20 人死亡，另有 19 人失踪。</p><p>截至周二，已有超过 5 万当地居民从家中撤离。据国有媒体《北京日报》报道，北京西部边缘的门头沟和房山郊区是受影响最严重的地区之一，一些地区报告出现电力和通讯中断。</p><p>据当地防洪抗旱办公室的一位官员称，截至早上 6 点，过去四天，这两个地区的降雨量已超过 16 英寸。这比他们预期的平均水平的一半以上，也超过了 2012 年该市上次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443437504577545020100937242?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重大洪水灾害的</a>水平，当时有 79 人死亡。</p><p>该市门头沟附近的斋堂水库自1998年建成以来首次放水，而一份官方报纸则刊登了洪水淹没北京郊区一家豪华酒店大堂的照片。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827281?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台风“多克苏里”引发的洪水已淹没北京部分地区。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在袭击菲律宾和台湾后，多克苏里周五上午在福建省登陆，然后继续向北席卷，给首都带来了十年来最严重的降雨。据北京电台报道，到周二下午，风暴已向东北方向移动，并可能减弱。随着市政府降低应急响应级别，市中心的一些公园于下午晚些时候恢复运营。</p><p>中国沿海地区经常受到太平洋热带风暴的袭击，但多克苏里带来的降雨和洪水规模却不同寻常。除了周边的河北省（据报道有 9 人死亡、6 人失踪）和附近的港口城市天津外，风暴还给东北部约 600 英里的吉林省和广东省带来了大雨。据国家气象中心称，向南数千英里。</p><p>与此同时，据该中心称，第二场台风正在中国大陆沿海盘旋。该中心表示，预计卡努将在未来几天登陆浙江或福建地区，威胁进一步发生洪水，但北京面临的风险较低。</p><p>据中国官方新华社报道，上个月，西南特大城市重庆发生严重洪涝，造成 15 人死亡，造成广泛破坏，迫使数千人撤离家园。</p><p>重庆发生洪水之前，中国北方发生热浪，气温飙升至华氏100多度。据国营《环球时报》报道，中国国家气候中心上个月表示，中国出现了过去六十年来最高的高温天数，其中北京、邻近的天津和河北省遭受了最严重的高温。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827284?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，洪水席卷了北京郊区的妙峰山。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ng Hanguan/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Rachel Liang <a href="mailto:rachel.liang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（rachel.liang@wsj.com）</a>和 Dan Strumpf（ <a href="mailto:Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Dan.Strumpf@ws​​j.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc<author><![CDATA[Rachel LiangDan Strumpf]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>洪水/海啸</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>洪水</category><category>潮汐波</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Myanmar’s Aung San Suu Kyi Gets Surprise Partial Pardon]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>赦免范围包括五项定罪，其中一项涉及对讲机。但这位前文职领导人仍将因其他罪行而服刑数十年。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="613" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827248?width=860&amp;height=613" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">赦免后，昂山素季将被监禁 27 年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：nyein chan naing/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">费利斯</a></span>·所罗门</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:14 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>缅甸前文职领导人昂山素季在 2021 年的军事政变中被赶下台，并在军政府针对她提起的一系列案件中被定罪，其中一些罪行被赦免，将她长达数十年的刑期减少了六年。</p><p> 78 岁的昂山素季在 2021 年 2 月 1 日清晨的一次突袭中被拘留，当时军方推翻了她当选的政府，使这个东南亚国家陷入混乱。她随后被判犯有腐败和选举舞弊等 18 项罪名，总共被判处<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-to-serve-33-years-in-prison-after-series-of-trials-11672405999?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">33 年监禁。</a></p><p>军政府在周二在国家控制媒体上发布的一份声明中表示，昂山素季因其中五项罪行获得赦免，其中包括违反与 Covid-19 大流行相关的规定以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-myanmar-coup-aung-san-suu-kyi-accused-of-illegally-importing-walkie-talkies-11612361563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">非法进口对讲机</a>。军政府发言人佐敏吞告诉记者，赦免将使昂山素季的刑期减少六年。这将使她在监狱中服刑 27 年，除非军政府做出涉及她的进一步改变或决定。</p><p>一位知情人士称，自 2022 年 12 月以来，她的法律团队一直未能与她会面，也未能证实有关昂山素季最近从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-sansuukyis-life-in-myanmar-prison-no-visitors-calls-or-news-11667080016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">首都内比都的监狱</a>转移到一所房子的报道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827249?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2015 年昂山素季在缅甸竞选。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>昂山素季领导的政党全国民主联盟在 2015 年历史性选举中大获全胜，这是该国 25 年来首次自由竞争的选举，并于 2020 年以压倒性<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-the-generals-and-how-myanmars-democracy-hopes-collapsed-11612542400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">优势</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-under-fire-abroad-wins-big-in-myanmar-election-11605248807?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">再次当选。</a>选举后召开第一次会议，拘留了昂山素季和其他官员，其中包括前总统温敏，后者周二也获得了部分赦免。</p><p>军方声称此次投票存在舞弊行为，但选举观察员予以驳斥。</p><p>政治分析人士表示，军政府可能打算通过周二的部分赦免来安抚外国政府，并做出一个小姿态，表明他们愿意改变。然而，分析人士表示，西方政府不太可能将这一发展视为真正的让步。</p><p> “我认为我们需要抵制住过度解读的诱惑。如果你看一下所有这些指控，你会发现他们显然是把她关起来并扔掉了钥匙，”泰国独立分析师、缅甸问题专家戴维·马蒂森 (David Mathieson) 说。 “缩短六年徒刑只是表明这些审判从一开始就是政治作秀，没有法治。”</p><p>政变突然结束了缅甸长达十年的民主转型，使该国重新回到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-coup-poses-diplomatic-challenge-for-world-leaders-11613049643?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球贱民的地位</a>，并随着西方政府实施制裁和投资者逃离而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-economy-is-in-a-free-fall-with-empty-factories-closed-banks-failing-internet-11618059258?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">使其经济陷入混乱</a>。主要由支持民主的年轻人领导的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大规模街头抗议</a>遭到致命武力的镇压<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a>并很快陷入武装叛乱。</p><p>军政府和武装叛乱分子之间的冲突此后蔓延到全国各地。军方试图通过不断升级的武力消灭对手，经常<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-militarys-attack-leaves-village-in-ruins-strewn-with-charred-human-remains-7228843b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">利用空袭轰炸涉嫌藏匿叛乱分子的村庄</a>。周一，军政府延长了紧急状态，实际上将承诺的选举推迟到明年，声称这是稳定所必需的。</p><p>据监测逮捕和伤亡情况的非营利组织政治犯援助协会称，自政变以来已有 3,800 多人被杀， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-detained-by-myanmar-military-simply-disappearwhere-is-my-mom-11619265604?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近 20,000 人仍被拘留</a>。政治家、艺术家、记者和其他人仍在狱中。</p><p>写信给费利斯·所罗门 (Feliz Solomon)： <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>昂山素季</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Ukraine, Amputations Already Evoke Scale of World War I]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>自战争开始以来，估计有数万人失去了肢体，这一数字在西方最近的武装冲突中从未出现过<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824318/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS<span>弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/bojan-pancevski" itemprop="url" rel="author">博扬·潘切夫斯基</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:08 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年 2 月，19 岁的乌克兰士兵鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰东南部扎波罗热周围的前线附近遭到射击。弹片将她的左腿从膝盖上方撕断。她紧紧抓住被切断的大腿骨，看着医护人员将她被切断的腿放进车里，然后将她送往医院。</p><p> “我手里拿着骨头……然后我意识到这就是结局，我的生活将不再一样，”丹尼尔基纳说。</p><p>根据假肢公司、医生和慈善机构此前未公开的估计，自战争爆发以来，已有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去一根或多根肢体，达尼尔基纳就是其中之一。</p><p>实际数字可能更高，因为患者接受手术后需要时间进行登记。有些人受伤几周或几个月后就被截肢。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">基辅的反攻正在进行</a>，战争可能会进入<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更加残酷的阶段</a>。</p><p>相比之下，第一次世界大战期间，约有 67,000 名德国人和 41,000 名英国人不得不接受截肢手术，当时这种手术往往是唯一可以避免死亡的方法。参与阿富汗和伊拉克战争的美国退伍军人不到 2000 名接受了截肢手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826535?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 与该公司的顶级 Genium 假腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥托博克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰政府没有立即回应对这些数据发表评论的请求。基辅对准确的伤亡统计数据保密，以免民众士气低落。但即使作为粗略估计，这个数字也揭示了俄罗斯 17 个月的猛攻所造成的惊人的人员伤亡——这一损失将持续数十年。</p><p>德国奥托博克是世界上最大的假肢制造商，该公司正在与基辅合作帮助截肢者，根据政府和医疗合作伙伴的数据估计截肢者人数约为 50,000 人。总部位于基辅的慈善机构胡普基金会估计，战争造成的重伤人数为 20 万人。据该基金会称，大约 10% 的严重伤害通常需要截肢。</p><p>这些数字反映了俄罗斯发动战争的方式，大量使用地雷和大炮、导弹和无人机袭击士兵和平民。</p><p> “我的祖父于 1919 年创立了我们公司，旨在帮助......从第一次世界大战中因炮火受伤返回的德国士兵，他们失去了手臂、腿或视力 - 这正是我们在乌克兰看到的情况，”奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 说道。</p><p>丹尼尔基纳在位于西部城市利沃夫的慈善基金会 Superhumans 的帮助下，接受了奥托博克的假肢手术，之前接受了五次手术。</p><p>她已经 20 岁了，一直在社交媒体上用“Unbreakable Rusya”这个昵称记录自己的康复情况。周一，她收到了奥托博克与美国军方合作开发的一款名为 Genium X3 的更复杂的腿，可以让用户轻松爬楼梯，甚至倒退行走。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼尔基纳在乌克兰东南部前线附近受伤。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Vlada 和 Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 是一名来自乌克兰中部克罗皮夫尼茨基 (Kropyvnytskiy) 的 24 岁前钢铁工人，去年应征入伍，在一月份的巴赫穆特战役中失去了双腿和左臂。受伤前，他身高 6 英尺 1 英寸，但现在用假腿站立时身高为 5 英尺 6 英寸。</p><p>克雷文科和丹尼尔基纳现在都与超人一起帮助其他截肢者。他们的社交网络激进主义和媒体形象使他们成为乌克兰苦难和恢复力的象征。</p><p>制造足够的假肢（其中一些花费超过 50,000 欧元，约合 55,000 美元）并不是主要挑战：更大的瓶颈是护理截肢者的专家人员，每个人都需要量身定制的假肢，Näder 说。基辅为每位军事截肢者支付高达 20,000 欧元的费用，但平民往往难以负担治疗费用。奥托博克为乌克兰人提供折扣，并为那里的医生和技术人员提供免费培训。尽管如此，许多患者仍必须依靠慈善机构来获得假肢。</p><p>去年俄罗斯入侵之前，乌克兰每年有数千人截肢，但据乌克兰医生和专科诊所称，其医疗保健系统现在已经不堪重负，许多患者等待新肢体需要一年多的时间。医疗康复中心网络 Unbroken 的高管奥列克桑德·科布扎列夫 (Oleksandr Kobzarev) 表示，去年仅利沃夫的医生就进行了 53,000 多例手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="867" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826537?width=700&amp;height=867" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">失去双腿和一条手臂的乌克兰士兵丹尼斯·克雷文科在乌克兰文尼察的一家军医院接受手术后与一名军医在一起。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="704" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826533?width=700&amp;height=704" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 与鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰超人康复中心接受治疗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Superhumans 首席执行官奥尔加·鲁德涅娃 (Olga Rudneva) 表示，她的基金会每月只能接纳大约 50 名截肢者。她估计自去年以来截肢者人数至少有 20,000 人。</p><p> Rudneva 说，患者最晚应该在截肢后 90 天获得新肢体，以避免萎缩和其他问题，但许多人已经等待了一年多。她说，截肢者中的幼儿尤其难以照顾，因为他们成年后必须更换多个假肢。</p><p> 7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在 2022 年 5 月敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。她的母亲玛丽亚在爆炸中部分丧失了听力，她说她的女儿晚上会被失去的肢体的幻痛惊醒，这是一种常见的神经系统疾病截肢者的情况。</p><p> Jennifer Ernst 博士是德国汉诺威大学医院创新截肢医学科主任，专门从事涉及神经与假肢连接的仿生手术。她最近为一名士兵进行了手术，这名士兵在一次袭击中失去了双腿，导致他的整个部队丧生。</p><p>与许多在严重创伤后撤离到国外的乌克兰患者一样，这名士兵也患有抗生素耐药性细菌感染，迫使恩斯特切除了重要的腿部组织。尽管取得了成功——一名患者的手臂被 3D 打印的骨植入物救活了——但她表示，大多数患者由于严重感染而不得不截肢。</p><p>去年，她的诊所收治了一名 16 岁男孩，他在一枚俄罗斯导弹击中基辅地铁站时失去了一只手臂。爆炸杀死了他的妹妹，但他们的母亲只受了轻伤。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824387?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年 5 月，7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：敖德萨市议会</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据乌克兰军方与美国军医小组分享的估计，在前线约 3 英里范围内受伤的 100 名士兵中，36% 的伤势非常严重，而所有部署的士兵中有 5% 至 10% 死亡。相比之下，部署在最近冲突中的美军中只有1.3%至2%在行动中死亡。</p><p>训练乌克兰军医的前军外科医生组成的全球外科和医疗支持小组负责人亚伦·爱泼斯坦博士说，自二战以来，西方军外科医生还没有见过如此规模的伤害。</p><p>虽然大炮和导弹是冲突初期造成截肢的主要原因，但现在伤亡最严重的一些是来自 600 英里前线沿线埋设的地雷。私人 KSM 诊所的医疗主任 Kostyantyn Mylytsya 博士说，每天有 40 至 80 名受伤患者到扎波罗热市的医院报案，其中包括来自约 25 英里外前线的截肢者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">风暴之影导弹使乌克兰的反攻行动能够打击前线后方的俄罗斯目标。 《华尔街日报》探讨了这种武器的工作原理以及它为何迫使莫斯科重新考虑其后勤保障。照片插图：Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Mylytsya 在战前专注于整容手术。现在他的诊所为截肢者提供治疗和康复服务。他说，“乌克兰的每个城镇都需要这样的中心；他们一定和牙医一样普遍。”</p><p>一名在乌克兰武装部队服役的前英国伞兵在六月份的一次地雷爆炸中失去了一只脚。去年四月，即志愿参战一个月后，他曾受过伤，当时一枚俄罗斯巡航导弹击中了他所在部队的总部。他在乌克兰和英国的医院住了五个月，但尽快返回了南部前线。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>战争将对乌克兰人产生什么长期影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>六月，他的部队对俄罗斯军队发动了夜间突袭，但遭受了毁灭性的损失。他的队伍在一所废弃学校的地下室里躲了一夜，然后再次发动袭击。他们驶过被摧毁的西部豹坦克、悍马车和布拉德利步兵战车。战友的断肢散落在地上。</p><p>士兵们用断棍敲击前进的道路，以探测隐藏的地雷。当这位 28 岁的男子在俄罗斯废弃战壕附近架设机枪时，踩到了一枚杀伤人员地雷。</p><p> “我尖叫着朝行进方向摔倒，很幸运没有撞到另一个地雷，”他说。</p><p>他被送往野战医院，医生保住了他的腿，但切断了他的大部分左脚。他说，袭击发生后，他所在单位的许多人都住院了。陪同他们的士兵大部分都死了。</p><p>现在，在美国等待治疗的他说，他打算回到自己的团，即使只是作为一名教官。</p><p> “这场战争是可怕的，现在我也成了残废……但我不后悔，”他说。</p><p>写信给博扬·潘切夫斯基（Bojan Pancevski）： <a href="mailto:bojan.pancevski@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">bojan.pancevski@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320<author><![CDATA[Bojan Pancevski]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>医疗设备/用品</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>医疗器械/仪器</category><category>骨科/假肢植入物/装置</category><category>诊断/治疗设备</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>医用器材</category><category>补给品</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>医疗设备</category><category>仪器</category><category>骨科的</category><category>假体植入物</category><category>设备</category><category>诊断</category><category>治疗装置</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Ukraine, Amputations Already Evoke Scale of World War I]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>自战争开始以来，估计有数万人失去了肢体，这一数字在西方最近的武装冲突中从未出现过<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824318/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS<span>弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/bojan-pancevski" itemprop="url" rel="author">博扬·潘切夫斯基</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:08 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年 2 月，19 岁的乌克兰士兵鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰东南部扎波罗热周围的前线附近遭到射击。弹片将她的左腿从膝盖上方撕断。她紧紧抓住被切断的大腿骨，看着医护人员将她被切断的腿放进车里，然后将她送往医院。</p><p> “我手里拿着骨头……然后我意识到这就是结局，我的生活将不再一样，”丹尼尔基纳说。</p><p>根据假肢公司、医生和慈善机构此前未公开的估计，自战争爆发以来，已有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去一根或多根肢体，达尼尔基纳就是其中之一。</p><p>实际数字可能更高，因为患者接受手术后需要时间进行登记。有些人受伤几周或几个月后就被截肢。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">基辅的反攻正在进行</a>，战争可能会进入<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更加残酷的阶段</a>。</p><p>相比之下，第一次世界大战期间，约有 67,000 名德国人和 41,000 名英国人不得不接受截肢手术，当时这种手术往往是唯一可以避免死亡的方法。参与阿富汗和伊拉克战争的美国退伍军人不到 2000 名接受了截肢手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826535?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 与该公司的顶级 Genium 假腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥托博克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰政府没有立即回应对这些数据发表评论的请求。基辅对准确的伤亡统计数据保密，以免民众士气低落。但即使作为粗略估计，这个数字也揭示了俄罗斯 17 个月的猛攻所造成的惊人的人员伤亡——这一损失将持续数十年。</p><p>德国奥托博克是世界上最大的假肢制造商，该公司正在与基辅合作帮助截肢者，根据政府和医疗合作伙伴的数据估计截肢者人数约为 50,000 人。总部位于基辅的慈善机构胡普基金会估计，战争造成的重伤人数为 20 万人。据该基金会称，大约 10% 的严重伤害通常需要截肢。</p><p>这些数字反映了俄罗斯发动战争的方式，大量使用地雷和大炮、导弹和无人机袭击士兵和平民。</p><p> “我的祖父于 1919 年创立了我们公司，旨在帮助......从第一次世界大战中因炮火受伤返回的德国士兵，他们失去了手臂、腿或视力 - 这正是我们在乌克兰看到的情况，”奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 说道。</p><p>丹尼尔基纳在位于西部城市利沃夫的慈善基金会 Superhumans 的帮助下，接受了奥托博克的假肢手术，之前接受了五次手术。</p><p>她已经 20 岁了，一直在社交媒体上用“Unbreakable Rusya”这个昵称记录自己的康复情况。周一，她收到了奥托博克与美国军方合作开发的一款名为 Genium X3 的更复杂的腿，可以让用户轻松爬楼梯，甚至倒退行走。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼尔基纳在乌克兰东南部前线附近受伤。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Vlada 和 Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 是一名来自乌克兰中部克罗皮夫尼茨基 (Kropyvnytskiy) 的 24 岁前钢铁工人，去年应征入伍，在一月份的巴赫穆特战役中失去了双腿和左臂。受伤前，他身高 6 英尺 1 英寸，但现在用假腿站立时身高为 5 英尺 6 英寸。</p><p>克雷文科和丹尼尔基纳现在都与超人一起帮助其他截肢者。他们的社交网络激进主义和媒体形象使他们成为乌克兰苦难和恢复力的象征。</p><p>制造足够的假肢（其中一些花费超过 50,000 欧元，约合 55,000 美元）并不是主要挑战：更大的瓶颈是护理截肢者的专家人员，每个人都需要量身定制的假肢，Näder 说。基辅为每位军事截肢者支付高达 20,000 欧元的费用，但平民往往难以负担治疗费用。奥托博克为乌克兰人提供折扣，并为那里的医生和技术人员提供免费培训。尽管如此，许多患者仍必须依靠慈善机构来获得假肢。</p><p>去年俄罗斯入侵之前，乌克兰每年有数千人截肢，但据乌克兰医生和专科诊所称，其医疗保健系统现在已经不堪重负，许多患者等待新肢体需要一年多的时间。医疗康复中心网络 Unbroken 的高管奥列克桑德·科布扎列夫 (Oleksandr Kobzarev) 表示，去年仅利沃夫的医生就进行了 53,000 多例手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="867" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826537?width=700&amp;height=867" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">失去双腿和一条手臂的乌克兰士兵丹尼斯·克雷文科在乌克兰文尼察的一家军医院接受手术后与一名军医在一起。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="704" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826533?width=700&amp;height=704" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 与鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰超人康复中心接受治疗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Superhumans 首席执行官奥尔加·鲁德涅娃 (Olga Rudneva) 表示，她的基金会每月只能接纳大约 50 名截肢者。她估计自去年以来截肢者人数至少有 20,000 人。</p><p> Rudneva 说，患者最晚应该在截肢后 90 天获得新肢体，以避免萎缩和其他问题，但许多人已经等待了一年多。她说，截肢者中的幼儿尤其难以照顾，因为他们成年后必须更换多个假肢。</p><p> 7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在 2022 年 5 月敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。她的母亲玛丽亚在爆炸中部分丧失了听力，她说她的女儿晚上会被失去的肢体的幻痛惊醒，这是一种常见的神经系统疾病截肢者的情况。</p><p> Jennifer Ernst 博士是德国汉诺威大学医院创新截肢医学科主任，专门从事涉及神经与假肢连接的仿生手术。她最近为一名士兵进行了手术，这名士兵在一次袭击中失去了双腿，导致他的整个部队丧生。</p><p>与许多在严重创伤后撤离到国外的乌克兰患者一样，这名士兵也患有抗生素耐药性细菌感染，迫使恩斯特切除了重要的腿部组织。尽管取得了成功——一名患者的手臂被 3D 打印的骨植入物救活了——但她表示，大多数患者由于严重感染而不得不截肢。</p><p>去年，她的诊所收治了一名 16 岁男孩，他在一枚俄罗斯导弹击中基辅地铁站时失去了一只手臂。爆炸杀死了他的妹妹，但他们的母亲只受了轻伤。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824387?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年 5 月，7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：敖德萨市议会</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据乌克兰军方与美国军医小组分享的估计，在前线约 3 英里范围内受伤的 100 名士兵中，36% 的伤势非常严重，而所有部署的士兵中有 5% 至 10% 死亡。相比之下，部署在最近冲突中的美军中只有1.3%至2%在行动中死亡。</p><p>训练乌克兰军医的前军外科医生组成的全球外科和医疗支持小组负责人亚伦·爱泼斯坦博士说，自二战以来，西方军外科医生还没有见过如此规模的伤害。</p><p>虽然大炮和导弹是冲突初期造成截肢的主要原因，但现在伤亡最严重的一些是来自 600 英里前线沿线埋设的地雷。私人 KSM 诊所的医疗主任 Kostyantyn Mylytsya 博士说，每天有 40 至 80 名受伤患者到扎波罗热市的医院报案，其中包括来自约 25 英里外前线的截肢者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">风暴之影导弹使乌克兰的反攻行动能够打击前线后方的俄罗斯目标。 《华尔街日报》探讨了这种武器的工作原理以及它为何迫使莫斯科重新考虑其后勤保障。照片插图：Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Mylytsya 在战前专注于整容手术。现在他的诊所为截肢者提供治疗和康复服务。他说，“乌克兰的每个城镇都需要这样的中心；他们一定和牙医一样普遍。”</p><p>一名在乌克兰武装部队服役的前英国伞兵在六月份的一次地雷爆炸中失去了一只脚。去年四月，即志愿参战一个月后，他曾受过伤，当时一枚俄罗斯巡航导弹击中了他所在部队的总部。他在乌克兰和英国的医院住了五个月，但尽快返回了南部前线。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>战争将对乌克兰人产生什么长期影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>六月，他的部队对俄罗斯军队发动了夜间突袭，但遭受了毁灭性的损失。他的队伍在一所废弃学校的地下室里躲了一夜，然后再次发动袭击。他们驶过被摧毁的西部豹坦克、悍马车和布拉德利步兵战车。战友的断肢散落在地上。</p><p>士兵们用断棍敲击前进的道路，以探测隐藏的地雷。当这位 28 岁的男子在俄罗斯废弃战壕附近架设机枪时，踩到了一枚杀伤人员地雷。</p><p> “我尖叫着朝行进方向摔倒，很幸运没有撞到另一个地雷，”他说。</p><p>他被送往野战医院，医生保住了他的腿，但切断了他的大部分左脚。他说，袭击发生后，他所在单位的许多人都住院了。陪同他们的士兵大部分都死了。</p><p>现在，在美国等待治疗的他说，他打算回到自己的团，即使只是作为一名教官。</p><p> “这场战争是可怕的，现在我也成了残废……但我不后悔，”他说。</p><p>写信给博扬·潘切夫斯基（Bojan Pancevski）： <a href="mailto:bojan.pancevski@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">bojan.pancevski@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320<author><![CDATA[Bojan Pancevski]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>医疗设备/用品</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>医疗器械/仪器</category><category>骨科/假肢植入物/装置</category><category>诊断/治疗设备</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>医用器材</category><category>补给品</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>医疗设备</category><category>仪器</category><category>骨科的</category><category>假体植入物</category><category>设备</category><category>诊断</category><category>治疗装置</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Nation’s Gun Laws Are in Chaos]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>最高法院推翻了法院对第二修正案案件的裁决一年后，法官们在历史问题上发生冲突——“整件事让我困惑” <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824106/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="2022 年休斯顿全国步枪协会会议上展示的半自动步枪。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 2022 年在休斯敦举行的全国步枪协会会议上展出的半自动步枪。帕特里克·T。法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>帕特里克·t。法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086927"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086927"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jacob-gershman" itemprop="url" rel="author">雅各布·格什曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-nations-gun-laws-are-in-chaos-587ded3f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-strikes-down-new-york-law-on-concealed-weapons-11655995248?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去年夏天，最高法院试图澄清其对第二修正案的广泛解读。</a>相反，它引发了混乱。</p><p>纽约州步枪和手枪协会诉布鲁恩案的判决规定，当今的枪支管制法必须在国家初期的武器法规中拥有明确的先行者，无论其背后的现代公共安全理由如何。</p><p>结果是：近几个月来数百起枪支诉讼案件<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/challenges-to-gun-laws-take-off-after-high-court-ruling-11658664004?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已经成为一场混战</a>，下级法院对于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judges-across-u-s-expand-gun-rights-taking-cues-from-supreme-court-11665432175?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">如何以及在何处限制枪支权利存在</a>冲突或困惑。</p><p> “所有这些都是对历史证据的挑选。 &#39;这还太早了。这已经太晚了。太小了，太大了，”美国第二巡回上诉法院法官杰拉德·林奇在最近一场关于纽约新法律的争论中说道，该法律禁止在公园、博物馆和酒吧等敏感场所携带枪支。 “整件事让我很困惑。”</p><p>在这种情况下，持有执照的手枪拥有者携带武器进入酒吧和剧院的权利可能取决于19世纪的法规，这些法规禁止醉汉携带枪支，并禁止在女士参加的社交聚会上携带枪支和屠刀。去年秋天判决的一个案件认为，联邦禁止序列号被抹去的枪支违宪，因为无标记的枪支在 18 世纪是完全合法的。</p><p>布鲁恩案引发了剧变。在该裁决中，最高法院表示，纽约州不能要求隐蔽携带申请人证明迫切需要自我保护。由克拉伦斯·托马斯法官撰写并得到五名保守派同僚支持的6-3意见表示，限制性许可规则侵犯了普通守法公民携带手枪自卫的第二修正案权利。</p><p>该意见拒绝了下级法院考虑枪支法的公共安全意图受到挑战的做法。法院经常发现政府遏制枪支犯罪和大规模枪击事件的目标高于枪支拥有者的自由利益。</p><p>意见称，这种做法削弱了枪支权利。相反，托马斯写道，为了通过宪法要求，第二修正案范围内的枪支限制必须深深植根于历史先例。为其辩护的政府有责任证明其法律与 1791 年第二修正案批准前后广泛实施的枪支法规相似或至少相似。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824108?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在 2021 年布鲁恩案口头辩论之前，迪昂·格林在最高法院与其他枪支暴力幸存者进行了交谈。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Leigh Vogel/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该决定以及最近最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-overturns-roe-v-wade-eliminates-constitutional-right-to-abortion-11656080124?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">推翻</a>堕胎权和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-says-high-school-football-coach-can-pray-at-50-yard-line-11656339266?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保护</a>公共领域宗教表达的案件，反映了保守派多数派对历史和传统作为宪法冲突仲裁者的重视。</p><p>法官经常进行历史调查来解释宪法文本并确定受保护权利和政府权力的范围。但在布鲁恩案中，高等法院从未要求如此严格地依赖历史证据来解决有关核心宪法权利的问题。</p><p>乔治梅森大学法律学者纳尔逊·隆德 (Nelson Lund) 表示：“我认为我在其他地方从未见过法院要求每一个疑难案件都通过包含如此少信息的历史记录来解决。”对布鲁恩决定持批评态度。</p><h3>分歧严重</h3><p>布鲁恩案的判决是已故大法官安东尼·斯卡利亚判决的延续</p>2008 opinion in District of Columbia v. Heller that first held that the Second Amendment protects an individual right to keep and bear arms for self-defense, not just the right of states to form militias. The 5-4 Heller decision was a defining moment for originalism, the judicial philosophy championed by Scalia that says judges should interpret constitutional provisions according to their meaning at the time they were adopted.<p></p><p> The Bruen decision extended Heller&#39;s understanding of the Second Amendment&#39;s text with the added constraint of the historical test.</p><p> Judges are at odds about how to use centuries-old weapons laws, many obscure, to evaluate modern-day restrictions and firearm offenses.</p><p> Some courts upholding the federal gun ban on pot users say the law is consistent with the tradition of keeping guns away from the mentally ill or unvirtuous citizens. Other courts declared the ban unconstitutional, citing a dearth of evidence that 18th- and 19th-century Americans who consumed intoxicating substances forfeited their gun rights. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="423" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824416?width=700&amp;height=423" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> At the time of the Second Amendment, the nation was a preindustrial, largely agrarian society.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kean Collection/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A similar split has emerged over whether the government can <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/domestic-abuse-gun-ban-in-peril-after-recent-supreme-court-ruling-ab1e5827?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">disarm individuals subject to domestic-violence protection orders</a> . A New Orleans-based federal appeals court said no, finding no parallel treatment of abusive spouses in early-American codes. Weeks later, a federal judge in California concluded the opposite, drawing on 19th-century statutes requiring individuals deemed a threat to public safety to post bonds before carrying weapons in public. The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-to-review-domestic-abuser-gun-ban-c50e3538?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Supreme Court will take up the issue</a> in its next term, which begins in October.</p><p> In 1791, when the Second Amendment was ratified along with the rest of the Bill of Rights, the nation was a preindustrial, largely agrarian society. Americans armed themselves with single-shot flintlocks whose cumbersome reloading and inaccuracy beyond a short range made them far less deadly than today&#39;s semiautomatic firearms.</p><p> Founding-era weapons laws, a complete list of which is still being assembled by academic researchers, were concerned with gunpowder storage, preventing accidents and keeping guns away from slaves, Native Americans and British loyalists. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="852" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824110?width=1260&amp;height=852" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A firearms training class in Upper Marlboro, Md., in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: andrew caballero-reynolds/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Thomas&#39;s opinion in the Bruen decision also suggested that laws in existence around 1868—when the 14th Amendment was ratified to protect federal rights from infringement by state governments—could serve as a historical baseline.</p><p> “This Court is not a trained historian,” US District Judge Carlton Reeves of Mississippi wrote in an order last fall. “We are not experts in what white, wealthy, and male property owners thought about firearms regulation in 1791. Yet we are now expected to play historian in the name of constitutional adjudication.” He floated the idea of appointing a historian as a consulting expert to assist him.</p><p> The Bruen case has placed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-judge-strikes-down-new-jersey-gun-law-11673306027?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a wide range of federal and state gun regulations in jeopardy</a> . In the past year, judges have ruled against bans on AR-15 assault rifles, laws restricting adults under 21 from purchasing or carrying handguns in public and other gun-control measures found to be lacking in historical tradition. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="810" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824121?width=639&amp;height=810" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ken Cedeno/CNP/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Courts have also slashed away at the federal Gun Control Act, originated in 1968, the once-presumed-untouchable law that makes it illegal for certain classes of people to possess firearms, including domestic abusers, drug users and those under felony indictment.</p><p> US District Judge Robert L. Miller last fall dismissed charges against a man who attempted to buy a gun from an Indiana pawnshop while under indictment. Though the government had been restricting firearm use by people under indictment since as far back as 1938, the judge said, that didn&#39;t prove a historical tradition under Bruen.</p><p> In the decision&#39;s concluding paragraphs, Miller said he earnestly hoped that he had misunderstood the Supreme Court&#39;s new command. “If not, most of the body of law Congress has developed to protect both public safety and the right to bear arms might well be unconstitutional,” he wrote.</p><h3> Historians as witnesses</h3><p> The case has given firearms historians new roles as key witnesses. California and other pro-gun-control states have assembled a roster of gun historians—compensating some at a rate of $500 an hour—to scavenge databases and newspaper archives for historic gun laws and render their opinion on them.</p><p> Days after the Bruen decision, political scientist Robert Spitzer got an email from the California attorney general&#39;s office looking for help in defending the state&#39;s 10-round limit on magazine capacity and restrictions on AR-15s. The professor, a retired academic who authored several books about American gun policy and the history of gun regulations, would be retained by more than 10 other states in the months that followed.</p><p> “It&#39;s been nearly a full-time occupation for me,” Spitzer said. He has dug deep into archaic restrictions on Bowie knives—the folklore-famed combat knife wielded by street brawlers and duelers—and spring guns—tripwire-rigged booby traps also known as trap guns that were once deployed against rabbit thieves and trespassers.</p><p> Courts have looked at those old laws as possible analogues to AR-15 crackdowns. California argues laws on spring guns are “particularly analogous” to its AR-15 ban in their goal of protecting the public from “unnecessary gunshot injuries.”</p><p> Gun-rights groups have recruited their own historians. They include Ashley Hlebinsky, a founder of University of Wyoming law school&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-gun-research-center-funded-by-firearms-executives-aims-to-diversify-debate-11674953998?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new center for gun research</a> and a former curator of one of the largest firearms museums in the country. The groups have also turned to Clayton Cramer, an adjunct community college instructor in Idaho known for exposing errors in another scholar&#39;s work on American gun culture and colonial-era gun ownership.</p><p> The dueling teams of historians have clashed in court papers, accusing each other of mischaracterizing past arms regulations. Spitzer and Cramer leveled accusations of shoddy scholarship at each other in a lawsuit challenging Chicago suburb Highland Park&#39;s ban on assault weapons.</p><p> In federal court rulings from Delaware, Washington state and Illinois that refused to block assault-weapon bans, judges said the crackdown on semiautomatic rifles resembled 19th-century restrictions on the carrying of Bowie knives.</p><p> “The &#39;craze&#39; for these knives led to their widespread use in fights, duels, and other criminal activities,” wrote US District Judge Richard Andrews of Delaware in March. “As violent crime increased during the early nineteenth century, states responded with anti-knife legislation.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824112?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> California Gov. Gavin Newsom has backed stronger gun-control laws.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nelvin C. Cepeda/The San Diego Union-Tribune/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In late April, however, a different federal judge in Illinois, US District Judge Stephen McGlynn of East St. Louis, Ill., ruled against the state&#39;s assault-weapons ban, rejecting the comparison to old Bowie laws. The analogy failed, he said, because the Bowie statutes didn&#39;t criminalize possession of the weapon—unlike Illinois&#39;s law—but mostly restricted the carrying of concealed knives in public places.</p><p> Illinois, the judge said, enacted the law months after a gunman shot up an Independence Day parade in Highland Park. “Can the senseless crimes of a relative few be so despicable to justify the infringement of the constitutional rights of law-abiding individuals in hopes that such crimes will then abate or, at least, not be as horrific?” wrote Judge McGlynn. “Likely no,” he answered. A federal appeals court in Chicago is now reviewing the state law.</p><h3> Gun rights of felons</h3><p> A federal appeals court in Philadelphia recently reviewed a federal law disarming people convicted of felonies and serious misdemeanors. It upheld the gun rights of a Pennsylvania man forbidden from arming himself because he once committed food-stamp fraud decades ago. In doing so, the court rejected analogies to early-American state laws confiscating firearms from Blacks, Native Americans, Catholics, Quakers and British loyalists.</p><p> Judge Reeves of Mississippi upheld in June the gun rights of a man convicted of aggravated assault and manslaughter, saying he was following the high court&#39;s reasoning in Bruen. But a federal appeals court based in St. Louis affirmed the indictment of a convicted drug dealer for illegal gun possession. The court noted that in the late 1700s nonviolent crimes such as horse theft or forgery were capital offenses—and in such a punishment one loses the right to bear arms.</p><p> The Biden administration hopes the case the Supreme Court will hear in the coming term will result in gun prohibitions being retained on individuals subject to domestic-violence protective orders. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824109?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> New York state is enforcing gun restrictions in certain sensitive areas, including bars, schools, hospitals and Times Square, shown in September.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Nagle/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A February appeals court ruling threw out the conviction of an Arlington, Texas, man for possessing firearms while under a domestic-violence restraining order after applying the guidance of the Bruen case. In its decision, the New Orleans-based Fifth US Circuit Court of Appeals said the domestic-abuse gun law lacked historical support.</p><p> The court said the man, who also faces charges on multiple shootings, was “hardly a model citizen” but said he was still “part of the political community entitled to the Second Amendment&#39;s guarantees.”</p><p> US Solicitor General Elizabeth Prelogar in the government&#39;s high-court appeal said the Fifth Circuit “missed the forest for the trees” and “overlooked the strong historical evidence supporting the general principle that the government may disarm dangerous individuals.”</p><p> Most of the litigation challenging criminal gun laws is spearheaded by public defenders, not gun-rights groups, on behalf of indigent defendants.</p><p> Within 48 hours after the Bruen decision, Lex Coleman, a federal public defender in West Virginia, was on the phone with clients, including Randy Price, an Ohio man caught possessing a pistol with an obliterated serial number in violation of federal law.</p><p> Coleman told Price they needed to file motions contesting the constitutionality of the charges against him. “The world has changed, and we need to go for this and see what happens,” he said he told Price.</p><p> He got the indictment on that charge overturned after prosecutors struggled to identify a historical statute similar to the prohibition on unmarked guns. “We&#39;re being forced under this decision to look back in time…quite frankly I find it really hard,” prosecutor Negar Kordestani told the judge.</p><p> In dismissing the gun charge, the judge found it “undisputed that serial numbers were not required, or even in common use, in 1791.”</p><p> Write to Jacob Gershman at <a href="mailto:jacob.gershman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jacob.gershman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-nations-gun-laws-are-in-chaos-587ded3f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-nations-gun-laws-are-in-chaos-587ded3f<author><![CDATA[Jacob Gershman]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Gun Control</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>gun control</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Obsessed Parents Overanalyze Photos of Their Kids at Camp]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Sleep-away camps try to put mom and dad at ease with photos of children having fun, but sometimes the shots instead stir concerns <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827035/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Texts between Dayna Solomon and her husband, Seth, about a photo of their son at summer camp." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Texts between Dayna Solomon and her husband, Seth, about a photo of their son at summer camp. Photo: The Susquehannock Camps <span>Photo: The Susquehannock Camps</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096370"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001096370"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Tara Weiss</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/obsessed-parents-overanalyze-photos-of-their-kids-at-camp-8b9920bf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Summer sleep-away camps regularly post photos of boys and girls during games, meals and assemblies, reassuring parents their children are alive and having fun. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          twocolumn
"><figure class="media-object-image img-twocolumn"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="140" height="140" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827709?width=140&amp;height=140" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Looking for good signs.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Many moms and dads aren&#39;t convinced. They scrutinize every pixel of their child&#39;s expression and body language for clues about their emotional state. These parents may want their children to gain independence at camp, but they can&#39;t help poring over photos to see if the kids are smiling, engaged in activities or circled by friends. Anything less—a child walking alone or caught in a neutral expression—triggers questions and deep analysis.</p><p> “It&#39;s an addiction,” said Stacy Johnson, of Manalapan, NJ Every morning, she scrolls through hundreds of photos looking for her 11-year-old daughter Liv, and her son Jace, 8. They go for seven weeks to Camp Chen-A-Wanda in Pennsylvania&#39;s Pocono Mountains.</p><p> Johnson is more concerned about Jace, a first-time camper. In a video from a dance party at Camp Chen-A-Wanda, she saw he wasn&#39;t joining the fun. She guessed he was sad because parent-visiting day had ended only a few hours earlier. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826627?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> From Left, Liv Johnson, Chris Johnson, Jace Johnson, Stacy Johnson and Noa Johnson during parent-visiting day at Camp Chen-A-Wanda.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Johnson family</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Obsessed parents gather evidence from photos to tell their campers via letters and calls to change their shirts or slather on more sunscreen. Others, desperate for information, offer children cash rewards if they try to appear in more camp photos.</p><p> Dayna Solomon, of Brooklyn, was disturbed by a photo of her 13-year-old-son Jake, a camper at Susquehannock in Pennsylvania. The boy was shown walking under a bridge made by the outstretched arms of campers. She immediately texted her husband, Seth.</p><p> “Hm. He doesn&#39;t look thrilled,” she wrote.</p><p> “You&#39;re nuts,” her husband replied. “He looks focused.”</p><p> Photo-copter parents hover a far distance from their own parents, who generally dropped them at summer camp with the expectation of maybe a letter or two. Some camps now livestream sports tournaments and other special events on Instagram. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827036?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jake Solomon on his first day at Camp Susquehannock.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dayna Solomon</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Heidi Green,</p> a professional photographer in Manhattan who has two campers, created the Instagram account Spot My Kid, which has 1,177 followers. She described her audience as “crazy camp parents who stalk, overanalyze and treasure every single sighting. (No matter how ridiculous.)” Parents share photos marked with circles and arrows that flag their child in a crowd.<p></p><p> “We&#39;re so desperate for a sign of life that we hold on to any little sign we can find, whether it&#39;s the back of our child&#39;s shoe, the top of their hat, their ear or them all the way in the back of a photo where we have to zoom in 100 times to see them,” Green said.</p><p> Tracy Seiler&#39;s son Brody, 10, has been attending Camp Westmont in Pennsylvania since age 9, and he was joined this summer by his 7-year-old twin siblings Ryder and Emmy. As an experienced camp parent Seiler knew not to freak out when she saw a photo of Ryder standing alone at the camp carnival. A couple of summers ago, Seiler, of Marlboro, NJ, saw a similar photo of Brody and recalled obsessing that he had no friends. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827024?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tracy Seiler&#39;s children Ryder, Emmy and Brody at camp.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tracy Seiler</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “Those thoughts build anxiety, and they run away with you,” said Stacy Fleischman,</p> director of business development at Camp Specialists, a service that matches children with camps. She fields calls from clients who sometimes panic about what they infer from photos of their children. “They can make a parent who isn&#39;t anxious become anxious.”<p></p><p> Tyler Hill Camp in Wayne County, Pa., employs photographers and videographers to document the daily lives of campers. Every age group has its own Instagram account. One videographer posts on TikTok, a new feature this year. The camp&#39;s opening day got around half a million views.</p><p> “We live in a different world. Kids coming to camp today are connected to their parents 24/7. All of a sudden that stops and they have an insatiable appetite for knowing what&#39;s going on,” said Wendy Siegel, the camp&#39;s co-owner and director with her husband, Andy. To keep pace with demand, the camp tries to capture at least two photos of each camper every day. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827037?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dayna Solomon hugging her daughter, Sydney, before she gets on the bus to summer camp.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dayna Solomon</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Six years ago, the clamor from parents about what they saw in camp photos prompted an email from Siegel that revealed some of the questions from moms and dads.</p><p> <em>My son isn&#39;t smiling. Please go back and take another of him smiling.</em></p><p> <em>Can you please make sure she knows that the blue tank top with the stripes is to wear at night—not during the day?</em></p><p> <em>Why is my son standing on the outskirts of the group? Do those boys not like him?</em></p><p> Siegel and her staff now remind parents that if there is a serious concern they will be in touch. Otherwise, she said, she advises them to embrace the philosophy that no news is good news. <em>&nbsp;</em></p><p> Parents may cherish that their children forgo technology while at camp, but many feel no qualms about using apps like Campanion and its competitors, which use facial recognition to alert moms and dads when a photo of their child surfaces.</p><p> Paul Berliner, president of Campanion, said the app was created to help camps manage hiring, payment, medical forms and profiles. The photo tagging feature was a natural evolution, he said, giving parents a way to more closely share the camp experience.</p><p> Johnson, the mother of Liv and Jace, goes through all of the daily camp photos even though she has the app.</p><p> “I still want to be a part of camp,” said Johnson, who worked at her own childhood camp into her early 20s. “A Campanion notification goes off and my heart flutters.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/obsessed-parents-overanalyze-photos-of-their-kids-at-camp-8b9920bf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/obsessed-parents-overanalyze-photos-of-their-kids-at-camp-8b9920bf<category> a-hed</category><category> Motor Vehicles</category><category> Recreational Vehicles</category><category> Lodgings/Restaurants/Bars</category><category> Lodgings</category><category> Campgrounds/Campsites</category><category> Educational Services</category><category> Sports/Physical Recreation Instruction</category><category>汽车</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Leisure/Arts/Hospitality</category><category> Tourism</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> motor vehicles</category><category> recreational vehicles</category><category> lodgings</category><category> restaurants</category><category> bars</category><category> campgrounds</category><category> campsites</category><category> educational services</category><category> sports</category><category> physical recreation instruction</category><category> automotive</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>leisure</category><category>艺术</category><category>hospitality</category><category> tourism</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Put ‘Great Sex’ on Your Vacation To-Do List]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Vacation sex can be an excellent way to reconnect with your partner, but sometimes expectations don&#39;t meet reality <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825716/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Andrea Mongia <span>Illustration by Andrea Mongia</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098092"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098092"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elizabeth-anne-bernstein"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://si.wsj.net/public/resources/images/CH-AA158_Bernst_NS_20100111195708.gif" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elizabeth-anne-bernstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">Elizabeth Bernstein</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/put-great-sex-on-your-vacation-to-do-list-198da577"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Matt Hughes wanted everything to be perfect to celebrate his 10th wedding anniversary. He took his wife to an oceanfront suite at a luxury resort and had flowers, chocolate and Champagne delivered. That night, the couple went to dinner at a French restaurant.</p><p> When they returned to their room, Hughes dimmed the lights, leaned in for a kiss—and heard a great, big woof.</p><p> Several dogs started barking in the next room. The couple tried to carry on, but the pooches proved too distracting. The front desk wasn&#39;t much help; the room&#39;s human occupants were nowhere to be found.</p><p> After several hours, Hughes, 53 years old, a technology executive from San Clemente, Calif., drove to a pharmacy and bought earplugs. “It was really frustrating,” he said.</p><p> What is it they say about best-laid plans? (Pun intended.)</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-workers-are-finally-taking-guilt-free-vacations-f5eb383f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Vacation</a> sex can be an excellent way for us to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/right-mood-wrong-time-get-back-in-sync-in-the-bedroom-11675744215?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reconnect with our partner</a> —and create memories we can draw on in the future. We&#39;re already focused on pleasure and adventure. The novelty of a new place can be arousing. Without the distraction of our daily responsibilities, we <em>should</em> have more time to make it happen.</p><p> Sadly, reality often intervenes. Noisy hotels, sunburn, hangovers and the boss who just won&#39;t let go can put a damper on things. These days, there&#39;s a more overarching problem, too: Many of us live in such a state of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stress-relief-walk-nature-science-11659388504?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">chronic stress</a> that our nervous systems are stuck on high alert. Even when we get away from our day-to-day worries, we&#39;re irritable, exhausted, unable to relax.</p><p> That&#39;s not sexy!</p><p> In reporting this column, I heard from readers about their vacation-sex challenges.</p><p> “My husband and I are laughing at your email. We are currently on vacation with 6 kids,” one woman responded.</p><p> “We stopped to have sex on a mossy patch while on a motorcycle trip, but the bugs, rocks and general outdoor reality really killed the mood,” said another.</p><p> “I got food poisoning,” said a man, who explained that his ex-girlfriend didn&#39;t fully grasp how sick he was. “This might have been taken personally, which might have led to our end.”</p><p> Research on sexual fantasies demonstrates our desire for a romantic interlude. Ninety percent of people have fantasized about sex in a hotel; 85% about sex in nature; 83% about sex on the beach or another exotic location, and 53% about sex on an airplane, according to</p> Justin Lehmiller, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-tech-will-change-sex-and-intimacy-for-better-and-worse-11615003201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a social psychologist</a> and research fellow at Indiana University&#39;s Kinsey Institute, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-kinseys-75-years-of-sex-research-says-about-us-11662464272?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">conducted the studies</a> .<p></p><p> Anticipation is a big part of the fun. It also can be part of the problem. We often imagine that a future event will be much better (or worse) than it turns out to be. Researchers call this affective forecasting. When it comes to vacation sex, high hopes can create pressure, which can kill the mood.</p><p> “If you feel you have to do something, then immediately you want it less,” says Amanda Luterman, a psychotherapist in Montreal, who specializes in sexual relationships.</p><p> If sex doesn&#39;t happen, it can feel not just disappointing but hurtful. One partner might feel rejected or taken for granted. Both might feel like failures who have squandered a wonderful opportunity—and spent a lot of money doing it.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Are you able to have good vacation sex?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Hughes and his wife, married 22 years, have had vacation-romance mishaps other than barking dogs. On a Caribbean trip years ago, their kids came down with hand, foot and mouth disease on the one night they had a babysitter. Last year in Italy, their daughter got Covid and the family quarantined. In Puerto Vallarta in July, they planned an evening alone in their room, but couldn&#39;t relax knowing that the kids—now teenagers—were at the hotel&#39;s pool bar likely having their first drinks. (Mexico&#39;s legal drinking age is 18.)</p><p> Hughes says he sometimes doubts himself when intimacy doesn&#39;t pan out on a trip. “I wonder, &#39;Are you really that into me?&#39;” he says.</p><p> So he&#39;s developed vacation strategies to keep the fire lit. He tries to stay flexible and keep the mood relaxing. He indulges his kids. (“Happy kids, happy mom.”) He also looks for fun activities he and his wife can do that are outside their comfort zone. In Mexico, the couple went disco dancing.</p><p> “I think the best way to focus on sex is not to,” Hughes says. “When people feel at ease and relaxed, the thing that you want to happen comes naturally.”</p><p> How can you make sure satisfying vacation sex actually happens? It may take some planning. Here&#39;s some advice.</p><h3> Schedule regular vacations.</h3><p> Put them on your calendar. This will give you more opportunities for a vacation-sex reset, as well as something to look forward to.</p><h3> Talk about expectations.</h3><p> Start with the vacation itself: What activities do you want to do, how much time together do you need, should there be limitations on work and screens? “This will help reduce opportunities for resentment,” says Marissa Nelson, a sex therapist in Washington, DC</p><p> Then talk about intimacy, including what makes you feel closer to your partner and any new activities you might like to try. Discuss what to do if things don&#39;t go as planned. Public Service Announcement: Try another time.</p><h3> Don&#39;t overplan.</h3><p> If you&#39;ve got every hour mapped out, you&#39;ll wear yourself out. You also won&#39;t have time to be spontaneous. Spontaneity is sexy, Lehmiller says.</p><h3> Don&#39;t hustle up until the last moment.</h3><p> Pack early. Finish up work and errands with time to spare. “You dramatically increase your chances of a satisfying sexual and emotional connection by priming your nervous system before your departure,” says Julia DiGangi, a neuropsychologist in Chicago.</p><h3> Be adventurous.</h3><p> Start outside of bed. Go somewhere new, or try an activity or food you haven&#39;t tried before. New experiences activate our brain&#39;s reward system, flooding it with neurochemicals related to pleasure and bonding—the same circuits triggered when we first fall in love.</p><p> Shake it up in the bedroom, too. (Even a new time of day counts.) “Vacations are about exploration,” Nelson says.</p><h3> Staycations count.</h3><p> Sneak away close to home sometime. Even one night is enough to reset, if you get in a vacation mode of mind, Lehmiller says.</p><p> Think of it as a “laycation,” Mike Dowd, an architect in Portland, Ore., told me. “It&#39;s a vacation where you stay home and hope to have sex,” he says.</p><p> Write to Elizabeth Bernstein at <a href="mailto:Elizabeth.Bernstein@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Elizabeth.Bernstein@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
